{
  "texts": [
    "In biology, if a neuron is stimulated in a repeated and prolonged fashion, for example by constant sensory stimulation or artificially by applying an electric current, it first shows a strong onset response, followed by an increase in the time between spikes.",
    "Hence the spike rate attenuates and the so-called spike frequency adaptation takes place.",
    "Experimental data from the Allen Institute show that 17 a substantial fraction of excitatory neurons of the neocortex, ranging from 20% in the mouse visual cortex to 40% in the human frontal lobe, exhibit SFA as shown in Fig. 2a, b.",
    "There can be different causes for SFA: First, short-term depression of the synapse through depletion of the synaptic vesicle pool.",
    "This means that at the connection site between neurons, the signal from the pre-synaptic neuron cannot be transmitted to the next neuron."
  ]
}